        "faqs": [
          {
            "question": "What if Mom's Social Security is just over the income limit?",
            "answer": "She can still qualify through the net income test. After deductions for medical expenses over $35/month and high shelter costs, her countable income may fall below $1,305/month for a single person. Arizona also has no asset limits for most applicants, so savings won't disqualify her."
          },
          {
            "question": "Can Dad keep his house and car if he gets SNAP?",
            "answer": "Yes. Arizona exempts all vehicles and the primary home regardless of value. These assets don't count toward any limits. The $4,500 asset limit only applies to bank accounts and investments, and only for households over the gross income limit."
          },
          {
            "question": "Do Mom's Medicare premiums help her qualify?",
            "answer": "Yes. Medicare Part B and Part D premiums, plus any medical expenses over $35/month, are deducted from her income before calculating SNAP benefits. This can significantly increase her monthly benefit amount."
          },
          {
            "question": "Will SNAP benefits affect Dad's other programs?",
            "answer": "No. SNAP doesn't affect Social Security, Medicare, Medicaid, or housing assistance. The only conflict is with FDPIR (Food Distribution Program on Indian Reservations) — he can't get both simultaneously."
          },
          {
            "question": "What if I live with Mom but buy groceries separately?",
            "answer": "If you're 22+ and buy/prepare food separately from your parent, you can apply as separate households. But if you share meals or grocery shopping, everyone in the household must be included in the application, which may affect eligibility."
          },
          {
            "question": "Can Mom use SNAP for grocery delivery?",
            "answer": "Yes. The EBT card works for online grocery orders through Amazon, Walmart, and Instacart/Aldi. This is especially helpful if your parent has mobility issues or lives in a rural area with limited grocery access."
          }
        ],
