        "intro": "If your parent is struggling with prescription costs in New Jersey, PAAD (Pharmaceutical Assistance to the Aged and Disabled) can dramatically reduce what they pay at the pharmacy. Instead of paying full copays through Medicare Part D, your parent will pay just $5 for generic drugs and $7 for brand-name medications. PAAD also helps pay Medicare Part D premiums up to the regional benchmark amount.\n\nThis program is for New Jersey residents age 65+ or those receiving Social Security disability benefits. Income limits are generous: $54,943 for single people and $62,390 for married couples filing jointly in 2026. Unlike many programs, PAAD has no asset test — your parent can own their home, have savings, and still qualify.\n\nThe key requirement: if your parent has Medicare, they must enroll in a Medicare Part D prescription drug plan. PAAD works alongside Medicare Part D, not instead of it. Your parent cannot be on Medicaid to qualify for PAAD.",
