        "faqs": [
          {
            "question": "Can Mom keep her house if she qualifies for this program?",
            "answer": "Yes. Your parent's primary home doesn't count toward asset limits regardless of value. They can also keep one car, household furnishings, and pre-paid funeral trusts up to $10,000."
          },
          {
            "question": "What if Dad's income is just over the limit?",
            "answer": "Income limits update every April, and there are four different tiers with different limits. Oklahoma will automatically place him in the highest tier he qualifies for. Also remember that if he works, over half of employment income doesn't count toward limits."
          },
          {
            "question": "Does this replace Medicare or give Mom full Medicaid?",
            "answer": "No, this works alongside Medicare. Your parent keeps their regular Medicare coverage, but the state pays their premiums, deductibles, and coinsurance (depending on tier). It's not full Medicaid with long-term care coverage."
          },
          {
            "question": "How much will this actually save on prescriptions?",
            "answer": "All tiers include Extra Help for prescription drugs. In 2026, this caps costs at $12.65 per medication. The exact savings depend on what medications your parent currently takes and their current Medicare drug plan."
          },
          {
            "question": "What happens if Mom gets denied but her situation changes?",
            "answer": "She can reapply anytime her income or assets change. Income limits also update every April, so someone who didn't qualify one year might qualify the next. The QI tier has annual reapplication anyway."
          },
          {
            "question": "If Dad is married but Mom doesn't need this program, how do asset limits work?",
            "answer": "Oklahoma has spousal protection rules. The spouse who doesn't need the program can keep up to $148,620 in assets. This prevents couples from having to impoverish both spouses for one to qualify."
          }
        ],
