        "faqs": [
          {
            "question": "Can my parent keep their house if they qualify for OHP long-term care?",
            "answer": "Yes. Your parent's primary home is exempt from asset limits if they intend to return home or if a spouse or dependent child lives there. The home won't count against the $2,000 individual asset limit."
          },
          {
            "question": "What happens if my parent's Social Security is $1,200/month — over the $967 limit?",
            "answer": "They may still qualify through spend-down options. If your parent has monthly medical expenses, those can be deducted from their income for eligibility purposes. Apply anyway — the caseworker will calculate if spend-down makes them eligible."
          },
          {
            "question": "Does OHP cover assisted living or just nursing homes?",
            "answer": "OHP's OSIPM program covers assisted living, adult foster care, and home-based services — not just nursing homes. This helps seniors get care in less institutional settings while staying in their communities."
          },
          {
            "question": "If my parent has Medicare, do they still need OHP?",
            "answer": "Yes, OHP can work alongside Medicare as secondary coverage. OHP covers services Medicare doesn't, like long-term care, and eliminates Medicare's copays and deductibles. This is called dual eligibility."
          },
          {
            "question": "How much money can nursing home residents keep each month?",
            "answer": "Nursing home residents on OHP keep approximately $77/month for personal needs ($90/month if they receive VA pension). All other income goes toward their care costs."
          },
          {
            "question": "What if my parent needs care now but the application takes time?",
            "answer": "Apply immediately — OHP can provide coverage retroactively up to three months before application if your parent was eligible during that time. Don't wait to apply if care is needed urgently."
          }
        ],
